,"options":["Arises from immature B lymphocytes","Causes severe bone pain","Diagnosed by lymph node biopsy","Originates from T lymphocytes","Presents with tender lymphadenopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHodgkin lymphoma is characterised by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells and is definitively \u003Cstrong\u003Ediagnosed by lymph node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E. The disease typically presents with painless lymphadenopathy and systemic symptoms including fever, night sweats, and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArises from immature B lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - Hodgkin lymphoma affects mature B lymphocytes, not immature ones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauses severe bone pain\u003C/strong\u003E - Pain is not a typical feature unless there is significant disease progression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOriginates from T lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - Hodgkin lymphoma is a B-cell malignancy, with Reed-Sternberg cells derived from B lymphocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresents with tender lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E - The lymphadenopathy in Hodgkin lymphoma is characteristically non-tender\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReed-Sternberg cells are large, abnormal B lymphocytes that are pathognomonic for Hodgkin lymphoma. Their presence on biopsy confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hodgkin lymphoma is diagnosed by lymph node biopsy showing Reed-Sternberg cells derived from mature B lymphocytes.","Hodgkin lymphoma typically presents with painless lymphadenopathy and systemic B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss).","Reed-Sternberg cells are large, abnormal B lymphocytes that are pathognomonic for Hodgkin lymphoma."],"references":["Frisch, B., \u0026 Bartl, R. (2012). Atlas of bone marrow pathology (Vol. 15). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Porwit, A., McCullough, J., \u0026 Erber, W. N. (2011). Blood and bone marrow pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Weniger MA, K\u00fcppers R. Molecular biology of Hodgkin lymphoma. Leukemia. 2021 Apr;35(4):968-981. doi: 10.1038/s41375-021-01204-6. Epub 2021 Mar 8. PMID: 33686198; PMCID: PMC8024192"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51234"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T22:02:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T22:15:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7500"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65794"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag